Dancer warms up in an “offstage” space that is in clear view of the gallery visitors – an architectural area of the gallery designed by Nick Mauss.
Installation view of “Nick Mauss: Transmissions”
The Whitney Museum of American Art
New York, New York
March 16 – May 14, 2018

Dancer strikes a pose inspired by the surrounding works of art and research on American modern dance in a piece collaboratively choreographed by Nick and sixteen dancers.
Installation view of “Nick Mauss: Transmissions”
The Whitney Museum of American Art
New York, New York
March 16 – May 14, 2018

Nick Mauss tells the press about how he researched his tribute to American modern dance against "Images in Mind," the corner mirrored mural that he created. Nearby, the 1924 marble “Forms in Space sculpture by John Storrs, the 1928 dancer-inspired plaster sculptures by Elie Nadelman, and other works Nick selected from the Whitney’s collection.
Installation view of “Nick Mauss: Transmissions”

New York, New York

dancebrazil.org Presenting four performances of Inura at the Skirball Center with choreography by DanceBrazil guest artist Carlos Dos Santos and a commissioned score by Cuban-born composer and conductor Tania León; with Ritmos (2008), Vieira’s homage to Capoeira, the Afro-Brazilian martial art unique to his home state of Bahia, and the Samba, Brazil’s iconic popular dance. Stay for a Q&A with the artists after the performance on March 20. Participants will include: Jelon Vieira, Ritmos Choreographer & Artistic Director of DanceBrazil Tote Gira, Ritmos Composer & Music Director for DanceBrazil Carlos Dos Santos, Inura Choreographer Tania León, Inura Composer Skirball Center for the Performing Arts at NYU 566 La Guardia Place (at Washington Square South) New York, NY 10012 www.skirballcenter.nyu.edu March 19-22
